  "prompt": "How are the types of nerve cell structured?",
  "response": "Nerve cells, or neurons, are specialized cells that transmit electrical and chemical signals in the nervous system. They have a distinct structure that allows them to communicate efficiently. The main parts of a neuron include:\n\n1. **Cell Body (Soma)**:\n   - Contains the nucleus and other organelles, which are essential for the cell's metabolic functions.\n   - Integrates incoming signals and generates outgoing signals.\n\n2. **Dendrites**:\n   - Branch-like extensions that receive signals from other neurons or sensory receptors.\n   - They increase the surface area available for receiving signals.\n\n3. **Axon**:\n   - A long, thin fiber that transmits electrical impulses (action potentials) away from the cell body to other neurons, muscles, or glands.\n   - Can be myelinated (covered with a fatty sheath) to increase the speed of signal transmission.\n\n4. **Axon Terminals (Terminal Buttons)**:\n   - The ends of the axon that release neurotransmitters into the synapse (the gap between neurons).\n   - These neurotransmitters bind to receptors on the next neuron, muscle, or gland, continuing the signal transmission.\n\n### Types of Neurons Based on Structure:\n\n1. **Multipolar Neurons**:\n   - Have one axon and multiple dendrites.\n   - The most common type of neuron in the central nervous system (CNS).\n\n2. **Bipolar Neurons**:\n   - Have one axon and one dendrite.\n   - Often found in sensory systems, such as the retina of the eye.\n\n3. **Unipolar (Pseudounipolar) Neurons**:\n   - Have a single process that extends from the cell body and divides into two branches (one acting as an axon, the other as a dendrite).\n   - Commonly found in sensory neurons of the peripheral nervous system (PNS).\n\n### Types of Neurons Based on Function:\n\n1. **Sensory (Afferent) Neurons**:\n   - Transmit impulses from sensory receptors (e.g., skin, eyes, ears) to the central nervous system.\n\n2. **Motor (Efferent) Neurons**:\n   - Transmit impulses from the central nervous system to muscles or glands, causing them to contract or secrete.\n\n3. **Interneurons (Association Neurons)**:\n   - Found entirely within the central nervous system.\n   - Act as intermediaries between sensory and motor neurons, processing and integrating information.\n\nUnderstanding the structure and types of neurons is crucial for studying how the nervous system functions and how it can be affected by diseases or injuries.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
